{
  "text": "We found that in both wild type and in mutH cells, high-fidelity ribosomal mutation (rpsL141) and over-expression of Tig, GroEL/ ES and DnaK chaperones decrease the mutation rate to create the most potent anti-mutator effect ever observed (in average, 10-fold in mutH and 3-fold in wild type, Figure 2A ). The frequency of cells with a MutL-CFP focus is reduced from 0.3% in the wild type (corresponding to the genetic estimates [CITATION_1] ) to 0.09% or below. The 3-fold anti-mutator effect (p,0.0001) in the wild type is mirrored by an average of 9-fold mutator effect in strains with lowfidelity ribosome (rpsD14) or deletions of tig and dnaK (groEL/ES deletion is lethal) exhibiting around 3% of cells bearing a MutL-CFP focus (Figure 2A ). The ROS levels and the levels of 8-oxoguanine, the most mutagenic oxidative DNA damage, remain equal in all strains ( Figure 2B ). This massive change in mutation rates is not due to changing amounts of the mismatch-binding MutS protein ( Figure S1 ) and a standard genetic method measuring rifampicin resistant colonies [CITATION_2] ( Figure S2A ) shows a robust correlation with the microscopic method [CITATION_3] , Figure  S2B , Figure S3 ).",
